Readme.md
     1έΗΤ# Commander.js
     2έΗΤ
     3έΗΤ[![Build Status](https://github.com/tj/commander.js/workflows/build/badge.svg)](https://github.com/tj/commander.js/actions?query=workflow%3A%22build%22)
     4έΗΤ[![NPM Version](http://img.shields.io/npm/v/commander.svg?style=flat)](https://www.npmjs.org/package/commander)
     5έΗΤ[![NPM Downloads](https://img.shields.io/npm/dm/commander.svg?style=flat)](https://npmcharts.com/compare/commander?minimal=true)
     6έΗΤ[![Install Size](https://packagephobia.now.sh/badge?p=commander)](https://packagephobia.now.sh/result?p=commander)
    61έΗΤ## Installation
    62έΗΤ
    63έΗΤ```sh
    64έΗΤnpm install commander
    65έΗΤ```
    67έΗΤ## Quick Start
    68έΗΤ
    69έΗΤYou write code to describe your command line interface.
    70έΗΤCommander looks after parsing the arguments into options and command-arguments,
    71έΗΤdisplays usage errors for problems, and implements a help system.
   147έΗΤ## Declaring _program_ variable
   148έΗΤ
   149έΗΤCommander exports a global object which is convenient for quick programs.
   150έΗΤThis is used in the examples in this README for brevity.
   177έΗΤ## Options
   178έΗΤ
   179έΗΤOptions are defined with the `.option()` method, also serving as documentation for the options. Each option can have a short flag (single character) and a long name, separated by a comma, a space, or a vertical bar (`|`). To allow a wider range of short-ish flags than just single characters, you may also have two long options.
   211έΗΤ### Common option types, boolean and value
   212έΗΤ
   213έΗΤThe two most used option types are a boolean option, and an option which takes its value
   214έΗΤfrom the following argument (declared with angle brackets like `--expect <value>`). Both are `undefined` unless specified on command line.
   254έΗΤ### Default option value
   255έΗΤ
   256έΗΤYou can specify a default value for an option.
   276έΗΤ### Other option types, negatable boolean and boolean|value
   277έΗΤ
   278έΗΤYou can define a boolean option long name with a leading `no-` to set the option value to `false` when used.
   279έΗΤDefined alone, this also makes the option `true` by default.
   342έΗΤ### Required option
   343έΗΤ
   344έΗΤYou may specify a required (mandatory) option using `.requiredOption()`. The option must have a value after parsing, usually specified on the command line, or perhaps from a default value (e.g., from environment). 
   362έΗΤ### Variadic option
   363έΗΤ
   364έΗΤYou may make an option variadic by appending `...` to the value placeholder when declaring the option. On the command line you
   365έΗΤcan then specify multiple option-arguments, and the parsed option value will be an array. The extra arguments
   366έΗΤare read until the first argument starting with a dash. The special argument `--` stops option processing entirely. If a value
   367έΗΤis specified in the same argument as the option, then no further values are read.
   396έΗΤ### Version option
   397έΗΤ
   398έΗΤThe optional `.version()` method adds handling for displaying the command version. The default option flags are `-V` and `--version`. When used, the command prints the version number and exits.
   416έΗΤ### More configuration
   417έΗΤ
   418έΗΤYou can add most options using the `.option()` method, but there are some additional features available
   419έΗΤby constructing an `Option` explicitly for less common cases.
   459έΗΤ### Custom option processing
   460έΗΤ
   461έΗΤYou may specify a function to do custom processing of option-arguments. The callback function receives two parameters,
   462έΗΤthe user specified option-argument and the previous value for the option. It returns the new value for the option.
   523έΗΤ## Commands
   524έΗΤ
   525έΗΤYou can specify (sub)commands using `.command()` or `.addCommand()`. There are two ways these can be implemented: using an `.action()` handler attached to the command; or as a stand-alone executable file. (More detail about this later.)
   567έΗΤ### Command-arguments
   568έΗΤ
   569έΗΤFor subcommands, you can specify the argument syntax in the call to `.command()` (as shown above). This
   570έΗΤis the only method usable for subcommands implemented using a stand-alone executable.
   613έΗΤ#### More configuration
   614έΗΤ
   615έΗΤThere are some additional features available by constructing an `Argument` explicitly for less common cases.
   625έΗΤ#### Custom argument processing
   626έΗΤ
   627έΗΤYou may specify a function to do custom processing of command-arguments (like for option-arguments).
   628έΗΤThe callback function receives two parameters, the user specified command-argument and the previous value for the argument.
   629έΗΤIt returns the new value for the argument.
   648έΗΤ### Action handler
   649έΗΤ
   650έΗΤThe action handler gets passed a parameter for each command-argument you declared, and two additional parameters
   651έΗΤwhich are the parsed options and the command object itself.
   700έΗΤ### Stand-alone executable (sub)commands
   701έΗΤ
   702έΗΤWhen `.command()` is invoked with a description argument, this tells Commander that you're going to use stand-alone executables for subcommands.
   703έΗΤCommander will search the files in the directory of the entry script for a file with the name combination `command-subcommand` (like `pm-install` or `pm-search` in the example below). The search includes trying common file extensions, like `.js`.
   704έΗΤYou may specify a custom name (and path) with the `executableFile` configuration option.
   705έΗΤYou may specify a custom search directory for subcommands with `.executableDir()`.
   725έΗΤ### Life cycle hooks
   726έΗΤ
   727έΗΤYou can add callback hooks to a command for life cycle events.
   754έΗΤ## Automated help
   755έΗΤ
   756έΗΤThe help information is auto-generated based on the information commander already knows about your program. The default
   757έΗΤhelp option is `-h,--help`.
   787έΗΤ### Custom help
   788έΗΤ
   789έΗΤYou can add extra text to be displayed along with the built-in help.
   830έΗΤ### Display help after errors
   831έΗΤ
   832έΗΤThe default behaviour for usage errors is to just display a short error message.
   833έΗΤYou can change the behaviour to show the full help or a custom help message after an error.
   860έΗΤ### Display help from code
   861έΗΤ
   862έΗΤ`.help()`: display help information and exit immediately. You can optionally pass `{ error: true }` to display on stderr and exit with an error status.
   868έΗΤ### .name
   869έΗΤ
   870έΗΤThe command name appears in the help, and is also used for locating stand-alone executable subcommands.
   884έΗΤ### .usage
   885έΗΤ
   886έΗΤThis allows you to customise the usage description in the first line of the help. Given:
   900έΗΤ### .description and .summary
   901έΗΤ
   902έΗΤThe description appears in the help for the command. You can optionally supply a shorter
   903έΗΤsummary to use when listed as a subcommand of the program.
   914έΗΤ### .helpOption(flags, description)
   915έΗΤ
   916έΗΤBy default, every command has a help option. You may change the default help flags and description. Pass `false` to disable the built-in help option.
   925έΗΤ### .helpCommand()
   926έΗΤ
   927έΗΤA help command is added by default if your command has subcommands. You can explicitly turn the implicit help command on or off with `.helpCommand(true)` and `.helpCommand(false)`.
   937έΗΤ### Help Groups
   938έΗΤ
   939έΗΤThe help by default lists options under the the heading `Options:` and commands under `Commands:`. You can create your own groups
   940έΗΤwith different headings. 
   947έΗΤ### More configuration
   948έΗΤ
   949έΗΤThe built-in help is formatted using the `Help` class.
   950έΗΤYou can configure the help by modifying data properties and methods using `.configureHelp()`, or by subclassing `Help` using `.createHelp()` .
   956έΗΤ## Custom event listeners
   957έΗΤ
   958έΗΤYou can execute custom actions by listening to `command` and `option` events.
   966έΗΤ## Bits and pieces
   967έΗΤ
   968έΗΤ### .parse() and .parseAsync()
   969έΗΤ
   970έΗΤCall with no parameters to parse `process.argv`. Detects Electron and special node options like `node --eval`. Easy mode!
   988έΗΤ### Parsing Configuration
   989έΗΤ
   990έΗΤIf the default parsing does not suit your needs, there are some behaviours to support other usage patterns.
  1023έΗΤ### Legacy options as properties
  1024έΗΤ
  1025έΗΤBefore Commander 7, the option values were stored as properties on the command.
  1026έΗΤThis was convenient to code, but the downside was possible clashes with
  1027έΗΤexisting properties of `Command`. 
  1042έΗΤ### TypeScript
  1043έΗΤ
  1044έΗΤ**extra-typings:** There is an optional project to infer extra type information from the option and argument definitions.
  1045έΗΤThis adds strong typing to the options returned by `.opts()` and the parameters to `.action()`.
  1046έΗΤFor more, see the repo: [commander-js/extra-typings](https://github.com/commander-js/extra-typings).
  1058έΗΤ### createCommand()
  1059έΗΤ
  1060έΗΤThis factory function creates a new command. It is exported and may be used instead of using `new`, like:
  1071έΗΤ### Node options such as `--harmony`
  1072έΗΤ
  1073έΗΤYou can enable `--harmony` option in two ways:
  1078έΗΤ### Debugging stand-alone executable subcommands
  1079έΗΤ
  1080έΗΤAn executable subcommand is launched as a separate child process.
  1087έΗΤ### npm run-script
  1088έΗΤ
  1089έΗΤBy default, when you call your program using `run-script`, `npm` will parse any options on the command-line and they will not reach your program. Use
  1090έΗΤ `--` to stop the npm option parsing and pass through all the arguments.
  1098έΗΤ### Display error
  1099έΗΤ
  1100έΗΤThis routine is available to invoke the Commander error handling for your own error conditions. (See also the next section about exit handling.)
  1110έΗΤ### Override exit and output handling
  1111έΗΤ
  1112έΗΤBy default, Commander calls `process.exit()` when it detects errors, or after displaying the help or version. You can override
  1113έΗΤthis behaviour and optionally supply a callback. The default override throws a `CommanderError`.
  1154έΗΤ### Additional documentation
  1155έΗΤ
  1156έΗΤThere is more information available about:
  1164έΗΤ## Support
  1165έΗΤ
  1166έΗΤThe current version of Commander is fully supported on Long Term Support versions of Node.js, and requires at least v20.
  1172έΗΤ### Commander for enterprise
  1173έΗΤ
  1174έΗΤAvailable as part of the Tidelift Subscription
