SECURITY.md
     1έΗΤ# Security Policy
     2έΗΤ
     3έΗΤTo report a security vulnerability, please use the
     4έΗΤ[Tidelift security contact](https://tidelift.com/security).
     5έΗΤTidelift will coordinate the fix and disclosure.
docs/deprecated.md
     1έΗΤ# Deprecated
     2έΗΤ
     3έΗΤThese features are deprecated, which means they may go away in a future major version of Commander.
     4έΗΤThey are currently still available for backwards compatibility, but should not be used in new code.
    22έΗΤ### RegExp .option() parameter
    23έΗΤ
    24έΗΤThe `.option()` method allowed a RegExp as the third parameter to restrict what values were accepted.
    34έΗΤ### noHelp
    35έΗΤ
    36έΗΤThis was an option passed to `.command()` to hide the command from the built-in help:
    44έΗΤ### Callback to .help() and .outputHelp()
    45έΗΤ
    46έΗΤThese routines allowed a callback parameter to process the built-in help before display.
    62έΗΤ### .on('--help')
    63έΗΤ
    64έΗΤThis was the way to add custom help after the built-in help. From Commander v3.0.0 this used the custom long help option flags, if changed.
    87έΗΤ### .on('command:*')
    88έΗΤ
    89έΗΤThis was emitted when the command argument did not match a known subcommand (as part of the implementation of `.command('*')`).
    98έΗΤ### .command('*')
    99έΗΤ
   100έΗΤThis was used to add a default command to the program.
   118έΗΤ### cmd.description(cmdDescription, argDescriptions)
   119έΗΤ
   120έΗΤThis was used to add command argument descriptions for the help.
   141έΗΤ### InvalidOptionArgumentError
   142έΗΤ
   143έΗΤThis was used for throwing an error from custom option processing, for a nice error message.
   171έΗΤ### Import from `commander/esm.mjs`
   172έΗΤ
   173έΗΤThe first support for named imports required an explicit entry file.
   187έΗΤ### cmd._args
   188έΗΤ
   189έΗΤThis was always private, but was previously the only way to access the command `Argument` array.
   203έΗΤ### .addHelpCommand(string|boolean|undefined)
   204έΗΤ
   205έΗΤThis was originally used with a variety of parameters, but not by passing a Command object despite the "add" name.
   227έΗΤ## Removed
   228έΗΤ
   229έΗΤ### Short option flag longer than a single character
   230έΗΤ
   231έΗΤShort option flags like `-ws` were never supported, but the old README did not make this clear. The README now states that short options are a single character.
   238έΗΤ### Default import of global Command object
   239έΗΤ
   240έΗΤThe default import was a global Command object.
docs/help-in-depth.md
     1έΗΤ# Help in Depth
     2έΗΤ
     3έΗΤThe built-in help is formatted using the Help class.
     4έΗΤYou can configure the Help behaviour by modifying data properties and methods using `.configureHelp()`, or by subclassing using `.createHelp()` if you prefer.
    20έΗΤ## Data Properties
    21έΗΤ
    22έΗΤThe data properties are:
    34έΗΤ## Stringify and Style
    35έΗΤ
    36έΗΤThe `Help` object has narrowly focused methods to allow customising the displayed help.
   118έΗΤ## Layout
   119έΗΤ
   120έΗΤUtility methods which control the layout include `padWidth`, `boxWrap`, and `formatItem`. These can be overridden to change the layout or replace with an alternative implementation.
docs/options-in-depth.md
     2έΗΤ# Options in Depth
     3έΗΤ
     4έΗΤThe README covers declaring and using options, and mostly parsing will work the way you and your users expect. This page covers some special cases
     5έΗΤand subtle issues in depth.
    15έΗΤ## Options taking varying numbers of option-arguments
    16έΗΤ
    17έΗΤCertain options take a varying number of arguments:
    30έΗΤ### Parsing ambiguity
    31έΗΤ
    32έΗΤThere is a potential downside to be aware of. If a command has both
    33έΗΤcommand-arguments and options with varying option-arguments, this introduces a parsing ambiguity which may affect the user of your program.
    34έΗΤCommander looks for option-arguments first, but the user may
    35έΗΤintend the argument following the option as a command or command-argument.
    79έΗΤ#### Alternative: Make `--` part of your syntax
    80έΗΤ
    81έΗΤRather than trying to teach your users what `--` does, you could just make it part of your syntax.
   104έΗΤ#### Alternative: Put options last
   105έΗΤ
   106έΗΤCommander follows the GNU convention for parsing and allows options before or after the command-arguments, or intermingled.
   107έΗΤSo by putting the options last, the command-arguments do not get confused with the option-arguments.
   126έΗΤ#### Alternative: Use options instead of command-arguments
   127έΗΤ
   128έΗΤThis is a bit more radical, but completely avoids the parsing ambiguity!
   148έΗΤ## Combining short options, and options taking arguments
   149έΗΤ
   150έΗΤMultiple boolean short options can be combined after a single `-`, like `ls -al`. You can also include just
   151έΗΤa single short option which might take a value, as any following characters will
   152έΗΤbe taken as the value.
   191έΗΤ### Combining short options as if boolean
   192έΗΤ
   193έΗΤBefore Commander v5, combining a short option and the value was not supported, and combined short flags were always expanded.
   194έΗΤSo `-avl` expanded to `-a -v -l`.
docs/parsing-and-hooks.md
     1έΗΤ# Parsing life cycle and hooks
     2έΗΤ
     3έΗΤThe processing starts with an array of args. Each command processes and removes the options it understands, and passes the remaining args to the next subcommand.
     4έΗΤThe final command calls the action handler.
docs/release-policy.md
     1έΗΤ# Release Policy
     2έΗΤ
     3έΗΤWe follow [Semantic Versioning](http://semver.org/spec/v2.0.0.html), and limit breaking changes to major versions.
docs/terminology.md
     1έΗΤ# Terminology
     2έΗΤ
     3έΗΤThe command line arguments are made up of options, option-arguments, commands, and command-arguments.
